    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="antithesis">
GROSS writes that consensus development conferences &quot;never get coverage inthe
media or by academic commentators on science and technology.&quot;</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="20" relname="span">  What follows
is a short bibliography of consensus development conferences, NIH style:</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="14" relname="list">

OTA. 1982. Technology Transfer at the National Institutes of Health.
OTA-TM-H-10. USGPO.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="14" relname="list">

Fredrickson, Donald. 1978. &quot;Seeking technical consensus on medical
intervention.&quot; Clinical Research 26(3):116-17.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="14" relname="list">

Markle, Gerald and Chubin, Daryl. 1987. &quot;Consensus development in
biomedicine: the liver transplant controversy.&quot; The Millbank Quarterly
65(1):1-24.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="14" relname="list">

IOM. 1990. Consensus Development at the NIH:  Improving the Program. National
Academy Press.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="19" relname="span">


These references I draw from my dissertation, which focused on the problem of
the &quot;boundary between politics and science&quot; at NIH. </segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="18" relname="span"> With respect to
consensus development conferences, the boundary problem has been the
inclusion or exclusion of social, economic and ethical issues.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="8" relname="elaboration">  Markle and
Chubin, not surprisingly, but also IOM, recommend their inclusion. </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="16" relname="span"> NIH has
been hesitant in doing so,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="10" relname="nonvolitional-cause"> at least in part because it brings them one step
closer to the highly volatile realm of health care policy (which NIH
distinguishes from health research/policy).</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="17" relname="span">  Even former NIH director Don
Fredrickson has said that NIH needs to include more economic and social
analysis in consensus development,</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="12" relname="concession"> but he suggests that this should be
included only to the extent that it has become scientific.</segment>
